The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Agartala, April 7 (PTI): An outbreak of the deadly bird flu in Tripura has been confirmed following which authorities ordered culling of 25,000 birds.          
	Tests conducted after hundreds of birds died in the past two weeks in Dhalai district showed that the disease was the cause, official sources said today. The state government has sounded a red alert to prohibit import of poultry from outside the state.                  
	Mumbai: Motorists in the city on Monday chose to honk their way through traffic, ignoring the polices appeal to observe a no honking day to reduce noise pollution. The city traffic police, which had made the appeal on occasion of the World Health Day, took action against over 6,000 motorists for violating no-honk rules.                  
	New Delhi: National Commission for Women chairperson Girija Vyas is set for a fresh term in office, with the Prime Ministers Office clearing her reappointment, government officials have said. The ministry of women and child development is keen to reappoint her. She is expected to hold the post till 2011.                  
	Kota (PTI): Honeybees have claimed three lives in Kota and Baran districts while 50 people have been admitted to hospital, officials said on Monday. One person died in Anta village of Baran district and another died in Jharoli.                  
	Jabalpur (PTI): Two students of a private engineering college drowned in the Narmada on Monday, police said. Ashutosh and Anand had gone to Jilhari ghat with their friends for a picnic and drowned while bathing in the river. Their bodies were retrieved by divers.                  
	 Porayar (PTI): Three men from a Tamil Nadu village caught a six foot long crocodile while fishing in a river on Sunday evening. The village administrative officer informed the forest department. Forest officials later took the crocodile to Nagapattinam.                                                                                                                         
